William & Mary enrolled 6,171 undergraduate and 2,087 postgraduate students in Fall 2012.<ref name="CDS"/> Women made up 54.7% of the undergraduate and 50.9% of the graduate student bodies.<ref name="CDS"/>

Admission to W&M is considered "most selective" according to ''[[U.S. News and World Report]]''.<ref name="colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com"/> There were 13,660 applications for admission to the class of 2016: 4,443 were admitted (32.2%) and 1,467 enrolled (an admissions yield of 33.0%).<ref name="CDS"/> Over three-quarters of enrolling students (79%) graduated in the top tenth of their high school class, 97% graduated in the top quarter, 86.1% had a high school GPA of 3.75 or higher, and the middle 50% range on [[SAT]] scores was 630–740 for reading, 620–720 for math, and 620–720 for writing, while the [[ACT (test)|ACT]] Composite range was 28–32 for the 25th and 75th percentiles.<ref name="CDS"/>

Undergraduate tuition for 2012–2013 was $8,677 for Virginia residents and $31,860 for out-of-state students.<ref name="CDS"/> 41% of the student body received loans, W&M granted over $15.1 million in need-based scholarships in 2011–2012 to 1,563 students (25.3% of the student body), and average student indebtedness was $24,344.<ref name="CDS"/>

===Law and medical school===
Sixty percent of W&M students go on to graduate school within five years of graduation.<ref name="adm3154">{{cite web|url=http://www.wm.edu/admission/?id=3154 |title=Facts & Figures &#124; Admission |publisher=Wm.edu |date= |accessdate=September 26, 2008}}</ref>

===Public service===
William and Mary is the highest-ranked national university for placement of its graduates in public or government service according to [[Washington Monthly]] Magazine.<ref>{{cite web|last=Barshay |first=Jill |url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/magazine/november_december_2013/features/selective_service047353.php?page=all |title=Selective Service by Zach Wenner, Jonny Dorsey, and Fagan Harris |publisher=The Washington Monthly |date= |accessdate=2014-08-21}}</ref>

